"1485":"1485","1474":"1474","1430":"1430","1472":"1472","1509":"1509","ABt 1452":"1452","19 December 1474":"19 december 1474","Dean Hundred, Essex, England":"Dean, Sussex, England","Newbury, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Newbury, Berkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","Newbury, Berkshire, England":"Newbury, Berkshire, England","Bromsgrove, Worcestershire, England":"Bromsgrove, Worcestershire, England","Chetnole, Dorset, England":"Chetnole, Dorset, England"},"en":{"1459–1509":"1459–1509","1459–1535":"1459–1535","1485–1545":"1485–1545","1485–1530":"1485–1530","1430–1509":"1430–1509","1434–1474":"1434–1474","1459":"1459","1535":"1535","1545":"1545","1434":"1434","1530":"1530","1485":"1485","1474":"1474","1430":"1430","1472":"1472","1509":"1509","ABt 1452":"1452","19 December 1474":"19 December 1474","Dean Hundred, Essex, England":"Dean, Sussex, England","Newbury, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Newbury, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","Newbury, Berkshire, England":"Newbury, Berkshire, England","Bromsgrove, Worcestershire, England":"Bromsgrove, Worcestershire, England","Chetnole, Dorset, England":"Chetnole, Dorset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bennett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the medieval personal name   Benedict  , from Latin <i>Benedictus</i> ‘blessed’. In the 12th century the Latin form of the name is found in England alongside versions derived from the Old French form <i>Beneit</i>, <i>Benoit</i>, which was common among the Normans. The surname has also been established in Ireland since the 14th century.","German: from a short form of the personal name   Bernhard  .","Altered form of French   Benet   or   Bennet   or of some other similar (like-sounding) French surname. Altered ending reflects the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Bennet","meanings":["English: variant of   Bennett  .","French: derivative of   Benne  ."]},{"name":"Bennitt","meanings":["English (Midlands): variant of   Bennett  ."]},{"name":"Bennetts","meanings":["English (Cornwall): variant of   Bennett  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Dittus","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Fritz, Kurt, Otto, Reinhold.","German: from a vernacular short form of the Latin personal name <i>Benedictus</i> (see   Bennett  )."]},{"name":"Benedict","meanings":["English, German, and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Benedict</i>, from Latin <i>Benedictus</i> ‘blessed’. This owed its popularity in the Middle Ages chiefly to Saint Benedict of Norcia (<i>c.</i> 480–550), who founded the Benedictine order of monks at Monte Cassino and wrote a monastic rule that formed a model for all subsequent rules. No doubt the meaning of the Latin word also contributed to its popularity as a personal name, especially in Romance countries. Occasionally the English surname may derive from Latin <i>benedicite</i> ‘bless (you)’, perhaps given as a nickname to an habitual user of the expression. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed the German variant <b>Benedikt</b> and many cognates from other languages, e.g. Hungarian   Benedek  , Slovenian <b>Benedik</b> (see   Benedick  ), and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Italian   Benedetti  ."]},{"name":"Bennette","meanings":["English (Cornwall): altered form of   Bennett  ."]},{"name":"Benett","meanings":["English: variant of   Bennett  ."]},{"name":"Bennight","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English   Bennett  ."]},{"name":"Bennison","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>Bene(i)t</i> + <i>-son</i>. See   Bennett   and compare   Benson  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Bennett was born in 1459, in Newbury, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas Bennett, was 29 and his mother, Lady Anne Selby, was 25. He married Elizabeth Selby in 1472, in Berkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1509, in his hometown, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1459–1509":"1459–1509","1459–1535":"1459–1535","1485–1545":"1485–1545","1485–1530":"1485–1530","1430–1509":"1430–1509","1434–1474":"1434–1474","1459":"1459","1535":"1535","1545":"1545","1434":"1434","1530":"1530","1485":"1485","1474":"1474","1430":"1430","1472":"1472","1509":"1509","ABt 1452":"1452","19 December 1474":"19. detsember 1474","Dean Hundred, Essex, England":"Dean, Sussex, England","Newbury, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Newbury, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","Newbury, Berkshire, England":"Newbury, Berkshire, England","Bromsgrove, Worcestershire, England":"Bromsgrove, Worcestershire, England","Chetnole, Dorset, England":"Chetnole, Dorset, England"},"fi":{"1459–1509":"1459–1509","1459–1535":"1459–1535","1485–1545":"1485–1545","1485–1530":"1485–1530","1430–1509":"1430–1509","1434–1474":"1434–1474","1459":"1459","1535":"1535","1545":"1545","1434":"1434","1530":"1530","1485":"1485","1474":"1474","1430":"1430","1472":"1472","1509":"1509","ABt 1452":"1452","19 December 1474":"19. joulukuuta 1474","Dean Hundred, Essex, England":"Dean, Sussex, England","Newbury, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Newbury, Berkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","B